MissionCommands.Message: Welcome to the Mercury-Atlas 6 historical mission. The cockpit is ready for full internal power and final checks.
T/M blockhouse, verify the station recorders are on, we're going to full internal at T -12 minutes and counting.
C/O (capsule operator), isolated battery to Normal (verify).
Isolated battery is Normal, ready now.
Standby on the ammeter, like to go blockhouse, external power off.
Roger.
[Look at the ammeter and press ROGER when ready to go to full internal power.]
C/O, read out.
OK, we're indicating 25 amps, main is ...
Main bus is 26.
Standby 1 is 27.
Isolated is 29.
Back on Main.
Fans are 113.
ASCS, 110.
Ah, roger. All Mercury stations stand by for status report at T -5.
C/O, make two-way voice check with CapCom before completion on channel 1.
Roger.
Hello CapCom, Friendship 7, UHF HI, Com check, how me? Over.
7, this is cape, reading you loud and clear, UHF. Over.
Roger.
[Bermuda] We would like to hold at 7 and re-run a [garble] sim. We lost our main power on the computer and we just want to check that nothing else has gone wrong.
Ah, roger. You got your power back? [Roger] What do you estimate?
[Bermuda] Somewhere between 5 and 10 minutes, guys.
Can't you expedite?
[Bermuda] Make it 5.
Roger. And hurry up.
CTC from Flight. [Go ahead Flight.] We got our power back on the computer, it will take us about 5 minutes to verify, we will keep you informed.
OK C/O, you understand the reason for the hold?
Fine, thank you, I heard Chris there when he came through.
Oh, roger.
All stations are holding at 6 minutes and 30 seconds, estimate 5 minutes.
C/O?
Go ahead.
Space craft manager Bill Moseley wants to adivce you all the hours are written off.
Very good.
CTC from Flight. [CTC: Flight] Mercury Control is go.
CTC: Oh, roger. Would you like to pick up the count?
Affirmitive.
All Mercury Stations, be adviced, in 15 seconds we will resume the count at 6 minutes and 31.
C/O, suit temperature control to red mark.
All stations, attention, this is Cape [garble], we have picked up the count. [C/O: Suite temperature control is at red mark]
Cabin temp control to red mark.
Cabin temperature control to mark.
All Mercury stations, at T -5, side tone 8, and give status and green light on request. 5 on the clock.
All Mercury stations, give status. AeroMed: GO, ECS: GO, [garble]: GO, Electrical: GO, ASCS: GO, RCS: GO, Comm: GO, T/M: GO, C/O: C/O GO, Flight: GO, Stoney: GO.
Mark, 4 minutes and counting.
Roger.
3 minutes and counting all stations, 3 minutes and counting.
C/O, when the camera switch comes on at T -2, verify cam and tape recorders are running.
Roger.
Minus 2 minutes, 40 seconds.
Minus 2 minutes, starting prime pressurization. Starting water systems on. Minus 1 minutes 55 seconds. C/O verify cameras and tape.
Cameras are both running.
1 minute, 15 seconds. System Power: GO, RF Systems: GO, Propulsions: GO, AMR telemetry: GO, ??: GO, Mercury Capsule; GO
[Final status check]
[Countdown]
Lift-off!
Roger. The clock is operating. We're underway.
Hear loud and clear.
Roger. We're programing in roll okay.
Little bumpy along about here.
Roger.
Standby for 20 seconds.
Roger.
2, 1, mark.
Roger. Backup clock is started.
Fuel 102-101, oxygen 78-100, amps 27.
Roger. Loud and clear. Flight path is good, 69.
Roger. Checks okay. Mine was 70 on your mark.
Have some vibration area coming up here now.
Roger. Reading you loud and clear.
Roger. Coming into high Q a little bit; and a little contrail went by the window or something there.
Roger.
Fuel 102-101, oxygen 78-101, amps 24. Still okay.
We're smoothing out some now, getting out of the vibration area.
Roger. You're through max. Q. Your flight path is good. Pitch 43.
Roger. Feels good, through max. Q and smoothing out real fine.
Cabin pressure coming down by 7.0 okay. Flight very smooth now.
Sky looking very dark outside.
Cabin pressure is holding at 6.1 okay.
Roger. Cabin pressure holding at 6.1.
Roger. Have had some oscillations, but they seem to be damping out okay now.
Coming up on two minutes, and fuel is 102-101, oxygen 78 102. The g's are building to 6.
Roger. Reading you loud and clear. Flight path looks good. Pitch 25. Standby for staging.
[Fire tower immediately with this mission command]
Roger. BECO, back to 1 1/4. The tower fired. Could not see the tower go. I saw the smoke go by the window.
Roger. We confirm staging on TM.
Roger.
Still have about 1 1/2 g's. Programming. Over.
There the tower went right then. Have the tower in sight way out. Could see the tower go. Jettison tower is green.
Roger.
Roger, Seven. Still reading you loud and clear. Flight path looks good.
Roger. Auto Retrojettison is off; Emergency Retrojettison Fuse switch, off; Retrojettison Fuse switch, off. UHF/DF to normal.
Flight path looks good; steering is good.
Roger. Understand everything looks good; g's starting to build again a little bit.
Roger.
Friendship Seven, Bermuda has you.
[Check all voltages]
[During the mission, auto and manual fuel values will be part of system checks. These will differ from you but use them to match your own consumption]
Roger. Bermuda standby. This is Friendship Seven. Fuel 103-101, oxygen 78-100. All voltages above 25, amps 26.
Roger. Still reading you loud and clear. Flight path is very good. Pitch, -3.
Roger.
My pitch checks a -7 on your -3.
Roger, Seven.
Friendship Seven. Fuel 103-101, oxygen 78-100, amps 25, cabin pressure holding at 5.8.
Roger. Reading you loud and clear. Seven, Cape is Go; we're standing by for you.
Roger. Cape is Go and I am Go. Capsule is in good shape. Fuel 103-102, oxygen 78-100, cabin pressure holding steady at 5.8, amps is 26. All systems are Go.
Roger. 20 seconds to SECO.
Roger. Indicating 6 g's. Say again.
Still looks good.
Roger.
SECO, posigrades fired okay.
Roger.
Roger. Zero-g and I feel fine. Capsule is turning around.
Oh, that view is tremendous
Roger. Turnaround has started.
Roger. The capsule is turning around and I can see the booster during turnaround just a couple of hundred yards behind me. It was beautiful.
Roger, Seven. You have a go, at least 7 orbits.
Roger. Understand Go for at least 7 orbits.
This is Friendship Seven. Can see clear back; a big cloud pattern way back across towards the Cape. Beautiful sight.
Roger, still reading you loud and clear. Next transmission, Bermuda.
Roger. Understand next transmission, Bermuda. Capsule did damp okay and turned around. Scope has extended, okay. Taking off the filter I had on it before launch.
Making electrical check.
[Turn the DC VOLTS selector and check Main and all batteries. Press ROGER when done]
All batteries 25 or above, on main. Going through orbit checklist.
[RUN the Orbit checklist]
Roger, Friendship Seven. Orbit checklist. [Complete the checklist]
Landing Bag is off. Emergency Retrosequence, off. Emergency Drogue Deploy is off.
Emergency Landing Bag is next.

Roger. Landing Bag was already off. I got it first and reported it. Retromanual is off, and we're all set. This is very comfortable at Zero-g. I have nothing but very fine feeling. It just feels very normal and very good.
Friendship Seven. Standby for retrosequence times.
[Optionally use the [C] MISSION TOOLS -> FORMS -> MA-6: Retrosequence times and write down the times. Press ROGER when ready to copy.]
Roger. Ready to copy.
Roger. 1 Bravo is 00 plus 17 plus 50.
End of orbit, 01 28 54.
Roger, 01 plus 28 plus 54.
Roger, end of mission is 04 32 47.
Roger. 04 plus 32 plus 47. Do I have okay for resetting clock? Over.
Negative, don't reset the clock. Your V over VR is unity, your apogee altitude is 138 and are you starting your control systems check?
Roger. As soon as we get done with this transmission. I understand am I cleared to control systems check.

[The Control Systems Check is a test of all control modes in order to assure their readiness as backups to the ASCS system. You can find the procedure in Mission Pad -> Checklists -> Mission -> Ref 4 - Control Systems Check. The in-game steps will take you through it. Press ROGER when ready to start]
Starting controls check.
[Record manual and automatic fuel on a paper or in the Mission Pad -> Notes section. Press ROGER when complete]
[Maneuver to -34 pitch and stop rates. Press ROGER when done.]
[Pitch up from -34 at 4/sec. Press ROGER when a 4/sec rate upwards has been achieved.]
[Observe rate damping to within 3/sec]
[Observe aux. damping to within 0.5/sec]
[Zero rate at 0 pitch. Press ROGER when complete.]
Friendship Seven. Anything to report on control systems checks.
Not yet, everything appears to be going okay. Am now on the yaw part of the check. Going off right on schedule.
Very good, very good.
[Initiate 4/sec yaw right. Press ROGER when done]
[Check rate damping to within 3/sec.]
[Check aux. damping to within 0.5/sec.]
[Zero rate at 30 yaw right]
Control so far is excellent. Very good, no problems at all so far on control.
Roger.
[Initiate 4/sec yaw left. Press ROGER when done]
[Observe rate damping to within 3/sec.]
[Observe aux. damping to within 0.5/sec.]
[Zero rate at 0 yaw.]
Aux Damp pulls it right in every time. No problems.
Very good.
[Initiate 4/sec roll right. Press ROGER when done]
[Observe rate damping to within 3/sec.]
[Observe aux. damping to within 0.5/sec.]
[Zero rate at 30 roll right.]
Friendship Seven, Bermuda. Do you still read?
Roger, Bermuda, still read you loud and clear. Still completing control check. Having no problem at all so far.
Roger, you're still loud and clear.
[Initiate 4/sec roll left. Press ROGER when done]
[Observe rate damping to within 3/sec.]
[Observe aux. damping to within 0.5/sec.]
[Zero rate at 0 roll.]
This is Friendship Seven. Working just like clockwork on the control check, and it went through just about like the Procedures Trainer runs. It's very smooth.
On UHF, if you read, go to HF.
Roger. Going.
Friendship Seven, Bermuda CapCom on HF.
Hello, Hello, Bermuda. Receive you loud and clear. How me?
Friendship Seven, Friendship Seven, Bermuda CapCom on HF.
Hello, Bermuda, Hello, Bermuda CapCom. Friendship Seven reads you loud and clear. Hello, Bermuda, Friend Seven. How me?
[Initiate 4/sec pitch down.]
[Observe rate damping to within 3/sec.]
[Observe aux. damping to within 0.5/sec.]
[Zero rate at -34 pitch.]
[Record manual and automatic fuel. Estimated is 5% from each]
Canary Capcom, Cape Flight calling, do you read?
Hello, Canary, Friendship Seven. Over.
Friendship Seven, Friendship Seven, this is Canary CapCom. Read you loud and clear, loud and clear. Over.

Canary, Friendship Seven. Roger. Control check complete. Capsule in ASCS and holding. I have booster in sight out the window. It's probably about 1 mile away and going down under my position and a little bit to my left. Over.
This is Friendship Seven. Everything is still Go. Capsule is in fine shape. Holding pressure at 5.8. Over.
Friendship Seven, Friendship Seven, this is Canary Cap Com. Do you read? Over.
Hello, Canary Cap Com, loud and clear on HF. How me? Over.
I read you loud and clear. Would you give me your fuel on your control systems check.
Roger. This is Friendship Seven. Control systems check was perfect. Control systems checks perfect, Over.
Roger, Friendship Seven, understand control systems check was perfect.
That's affirmative.
Friendship Seven, this Canary Cap Com. Could you get started with your station report? Over.
Hello, Canary, Friend Seven. Repeat please. Over.
What is your space, spacecraft station, status report?
This is Friendship Seven. Standby. I'm getting out some equipment. Over.
Hello, Canary, Friendship Seven, switching to UHF. Over.
Hello, Canary, Friendship Seven on UHF. How now? Over.
I read you loud and clear.
Roger, understand loud and clear. I read you much better also, than I did on, on HF. Over.
Same here.
[Next flight plan item is the 30-minute report]
Friendship Seven, Friendship Seven. What is your spacecraft status report? Over.

Roger. Standby, Will give status report. I am in orbit attitude for your tracking. I am on ASCS at present time. The clock is still set for time to ret, for retrograde time of 04 plus 32 plus 28. I have retrograde times okay from Bermuda. Cabin pressure holding steady at 5.7.

The horizon is a brilliant, a brilliant blue. There, I have the mainland in sight at present time coming tip on the scope, and have Canaries in sight out through the window and picked them up on the scope just before I saw them out of the window. Over.
[Next item on the flight plan is a blood pressure check and Africa observations]
Roger, Friendship Seven. This is Canary CapCom. Repeat blood pressure check, repeat blood pressure check.
Roger, repeating blood pressure check now. Starting.
[Press the Blood Pressure check START button.]
This is Friendship Seven. Have beautiful view of the African Coast, both in the scope, and out the window. Out the window is by far the best view.
Roger, I read you. We're getting the blood pressure now.
Roger, Friendship Seven.
Friendship Seven this is Canary CapCom. Your, your medical status is green; it looks okay.
Roger. This is Friendship Seven. What is blood pressure? Over.
Friendship Seven. Your blood pressure is 120 over 80, repeat 120 over 80.
Roger.
[Stop the Blood Pressure check by pressing the STOP button]
[Open the Mission Pad -> Checklists -> Mission -> Ref 21 - Landmarks and start to observe. During the first orbit, try to identify and see the comments on this list.]
Friendship Seven, this is Kano Cap Com, I read you loud and clear. How do you read me? Over.
Roger, Kano, loud and clear; how me?
Roger, loud and clear. What is your status? Over.
This is Friendship Seven. My status is excellent. I feel fine. Over.
Friendship Seven. We have TM solid. If you want, we will standby while you do your yaw maneuver and check your systems.
Roger, this is Friendship Seven, starting in yaw maneuver.
[RUN the REF 5 - YAW MNVR checklist]
Going to manual control. Correction, going to fly-by-wire. Over.
Roger, understand on fly-by-wire for yaw maneuver.
[Press ROGER when you have established a yaw rate of 1/sec]
This is Friendship Seven, having no trouble controlling on fly-by-wire. Drift is coming around at about 1 per second, and holding attitude okay in other axes. Over.
Roger. Check drift at 1 per second and holding attitude okay all axes, I have your retrosequence time for Area 1 Charlie.
Standby. Will get it later. I'm in the middle of yaw maneuver at present time. Over.
Standing by.
[Follow the checklist and get to a stable attitude at yaw right 60. Press ROGER when complete]
This is Friendship Seven at 60 right yaw, and holding temporarily. Over.
Roger. 60 right yaw and holding.
[Make the observations and complete the checklist.]
Friendship Seven, I check your returning to orbit attitude.
You want to stand by for retrosequence time, Area 1 Charlie?

Roger. Going back on ASCS. Yaw check okay. Can pick up yaw fairly well in the scope. It's a little different display than I had really anticipated, but it checks okay, and I can pick up yaw. I have to be about 5 or so in yaw before I really start picking it up. Over.
[Press ROGER when you are ready to copy retrosequence time Area 1 Charlie]
Seven, you are fading rapidly. I will broadcast this time in the blind for Area 1 Charlie, 00 32 12, 00 32 12.
00 32 22. Is that affirm? Over.
[Manually follow and complete the Checklists -> Systems -> Pre-Dark checklist over the next minute or two]
This is Friendship Seven. Hello, Zanzibar, Friendship Seven. Do you receive? Over.
Friendship Seven, Friendship Seven, this is Zanzibar Com Tech transmitting on HF, UHF, do you copy? Over.
Roger, Zanzibar Com Tech, read you loud and clear. Control fuel is 90 98 cabin pressure, 5.6 and holding; oxygen, 75-100. Over.
Message from IOS Cap Com, that he will not release balloon flare this orbit. Will fire parachute flares instead. Did you copy? Over.
Roger, this is Friendship Seven, understand.
Friendship Seven, this is Zanzibar Cap Com. We have solid telemetry contact, report your status. Over.
Roger, this is Friendship Seven. Fuel 90-98, cabin pressure 55 and holding, oxygen 75-100, amps 24. Over.
Roger, Friendship Seven, this is Zanzibar Cap Com. Proceed with 30-minute report. Over.
Roger, this is Friendship Seven. Standby one.
[Next on the flight plan is a 30 minute check. RUN the 30-minute check checklist]
[Complete the checklist]

This is Friendship Seven. The head movements caused no sensations, whatsoever. Feel fine. Reach test, I can hit directly to any spot that I want to hit. I have no problem reaching for knobs and have adjusted to zero-g very easily, much easier than I really thought I would. I have excellent vision of the charts, no astigmatism or any malfunctions at all.

Friendship Seven, this is Zanzibar Surgeon, received your report indicating good reach accuracy. No disturbances on head motion, good visual acuity including astigmatism test and good response to exercise. Over.
Friendship Seven. Are you ready to copy your Contingency Area 1 Delta retrosequence time? Over.
[Open the Retrosequence time form and press ROGER when ready to copy]
Roger. Say 1 Delta.
1 Delta is 00 50 24. Did you copy? Over.
Roger. 00 50 24 for 1 Delta.
Hello Friendship Seven, Friendship Seven. This is Indian Com Tech on HF UHF. How do you read? Over.
Indian Com Tech, Friendship Seven. Loud and clear, how me?
Roger, Friendship Seven, reading you loud and clear
This is Friendship Seven. Had a beautiful sunset and can see the light way out almost up to the northern horizon.
[Garble]
Indian Cap Com, I'm receiving you very garbled. Over.
Would you give me your status and consumable readings please? Over.
Roger. This is Friendship Seven. My status is very good. I feel fine. Fuel is 90-98, oxygen 75-100, amps, 21 present time, cabin pressure holding at 5.5. Over.
Roger, understand, reading you loud and clear now. Over.

This is Friendship Seven. At this, MARK, at this present time, I still have some clouds visible below me, the sunset was beautiful. It went down very rapidly. I still have a brilliant blue band clear across the horizon almost covering my whole window. The redness of the sunset I can still see through some of the clouds way over to the left of my course. Over.
The sky above is absolutely black, completely black. I can see stars though up above. I do not have any of the constellations identified as yet. Over.
Roger, understand Friendship Seven.
Friendship Seven. Would you confirm you received retrosequence time 1 Delta from Zanzibar? Over.
This is Friendship Seven. Roger, 1 Delta is 00 50 24.
Roger. I have areas 1 Echo, Foxtrot, and Hotel. Are you prepared to copy? Over.
[Press ROGER when you are ready to copy the retrosequence times. You can use the MISSION TOOLS -> FORMS -> MA-6 Retrosequence times form]
All right, go ahead with retrotimes. Over.
Roger. Area 1 Echo is one hour, 15 minutes, 42 seconds. I say again, one hour, 15 minutes, 42 seconds. Over.
Roger. One Echo is 01 plus 15 plus 42.
[COPY]
Roger. Area Foxtrot is one hour, 28 minutes, 50 seconds. I say again, one hour, 28 minutes, 50 seconds.
Roger. Foxtrot is 01 plus 28 plus 50.
[COPY]
That is affirmative. Area Hotel is four hours, 32 minutes, 42 seconds. Four hours, 32 minutes, 42 seconds. Over.
Roger. 04 plus 32 plus 42. Over.
[COPY]
Roger. That is affirmative. Over.
[Next up is the Night Horizon check. RUN the Mission Pad -> Checklists -> Mission -> REF 23 - Day/Night Horizon checklist]
[Complete the checklist]

This is Friendship Seven. I am having no trouble at all seeing the night horizon. I think the moon is probably coming up behind me. Yes, I can see it in the scope back here and it's making a very white light on the clouds below. Over.
Roger, understand. Friendship Seven, we have launched our flare. You understand it is [...]. Over.
That is affirmative.
We have been advised that it has been ignited. Do you see anything? Over.
This is Friendship Seven. Negative. I don't have anything in the scope or out the window.
Roger, understand.
Friendship Seven, this is Indian Cap Com. Do you have any feelings from weightlessness? Over.
This is Friendship Seven. Negative, I feel fine so far. Over.
Roger, understand. What is your control mode? Over.
Control mode is ASCS automatic. Over.
Friendship Seven, this is Indiana CapCom. We now have LOS. Over.
Roger, understand LOS.

This is Friendship Seven, broadcasting in the blind. Wait a minute. Friendship Seven, broadcasting in the blind, making observations on night outside. There seems to be a high layer way up above the horizon; much higher than anything I saw on the daylight side.

The stars seem to go through it and then go on down toward the real horizon. It would appear to be possibly some 7 or 8 degrees wide. I can see the clouds down below it; then a dark band, then a lighter band that the stars shine right through as they come down toward the horizon.
Friendship Seven, Muchea Com Tech. We read you. Would you call again.
Hello, Muchea Com Tech. This is Friendship Seven, reading you loud and clear. How me?
Roger, Friendship Seven. Muchea Cap Com. How me? Over.
Roger. How are you doing Gordo? We're doing real fine up here. Everything is going very well. Over.
John, you sound good.
Roger. Control fuel is 90-100, oxygen is 75-100, amps are 22, all systems are still go. Having no problems at all. Control system operating fine. Over.
Roger. Do you have any star or weather or landmark observations as yet? Over.

Roger. I was just making some to the recorder. The only unusual thing I have noticed is a rather high, what would appear to be a haze layer up some 7 or 8 degrees above the horizon on the night side. The stars I can see through it as they go down toward the real horizon, but it is a very visible single band or layer pretty well up above the normal horizon. Over.
Roger, very interesting.
Shortly you may observe some lights down there. You want to take a check on that to your right? Over.
Roger. I'm all set to see if I can't get them in sight.
[Keep observing according to the REF 21 checklist as city lights may become visible]
Any symptoms of vertigo or nausea at all? Over.
Negative, no symptoms whatsoever. I feel fine. Over.
That was sure a short day.
Say again, Friendship Seven.
That was about the shortest day I've ever run into.
Kinda passes rapidly, huh.
Yes Sir.
I do have the lights in sight on the ground. Over.
Roger. Is it just off to your right there?
That's affirmative. Just to my right I can see a big pattern of lights apparently right on the coast. I can see the outline of a town and a very bright light just to the south of it.
Perth and Rockingham, you're seeing there.
Roger. The lights show up very well and thank everybody for turning them on, will you?
We sure will, John.

Very fine. On down farther to the south and inland, I can see more lights. There are two, actually four patterns in that area. And also, coming into sight in the window now is another one almost down under me. The lights are very clear from up here.
Roger. Sounds good.
Friendship Seven, Friendship Seven. This is Woomera Cap Com, reading you loud and clear. We have TM solid. Woomera standing by.
Roger, Woomera.
Roger, Friendship Seven. Let's go ahead with this 30-minute report please.
[RUN the 30 minute report from Mission Pad -> Checklists -> Mission -> Ref 11 - 30-minute report]
[Complete the activity]

Have gone through head movements and I get no effect from that. Have gone through the reach test and have no problem with that at all. My orientation is good, vision is clear. My moving target, looking at a light spot back and forth causes no ill effects whatsoever.
Roger, Friendship Seven.
Hello Friendship Seven, Woomera Cap Com. Do you read me? Over.
Roger, Woomera Cap Com. Still read you loud and clear. How me?

Weak but readable, Friendship Seven. All systems appear go at this time. Blood pressure reading 125 over 90. You have an HF check coming up in about 2 minutes and 30 seconds, and Canton acquisition approximately 7 minutes. Over.
Roger, Friendship Seven. Thank you very much. All systems are still go at this time. Switching to HF. Over.
Roger, Friendship Seven. This is Woomera Cap Com. Out.
[Switch to UHF]
Friendship Seven. This is Canton Com Tech. Do you read? Over.
Hello Canton. Hello Canton, Friendship Seven. Read you loud and clear. How me? Over.
Friendship Seven, Canton Com Tech. Read you loud and clear, also. Stand by for Cap Com.
Seven, this is Canton Cap Com. Go ahead. Over.
Roger, Canton Cap Com. My report follows: Fuel 90 100, oxygen 73-100, amps 22, cabin pressure holding steady at 5.5 Over.
Roger, Friendship Seven. Canton standing by.
Roger, Friendship Seven.
This is Friendship Seven, preparing to eat. Over.
Roger, Friendship Seven.
This is Friendship Seven. Having no trouble at all eating, very good. In the periscope, I can see the brilliant blue horizon coming up behind me, approaching sunrise. Over.
Roger, Friendship Seven. You are very lucky.
You're right. Man, this is beautiful.

This is Friendship Seven. I'll try to describe what I'm in here. I am in a big mass of some very small particles, that are brilliantly lit up like they're luminescent. I never saw anything like it. They round a little; they're coming by the capsule, and they look like little stars. A whole shower of them coming by.
They swirl around the capsule and go in front of the window and they're all brilliantly lighted. They probably average maybe 7 or 8 feet apart, but I can see them all down below me, also.
Roger, Friendship Seven. Can you hear any impact with the capsule? Over.

Negative, negative. They're very slow; they're not going away from me more than maybe 3 or 4 miles per hour. They're going at the same speed I am approximately. They're only very slightly under my speed. Over.
They do, they do have a different motion, though, from me because they swirl around the capsule and then depart back the way I am looking. Are you receiving? Over.
There are literally thousands of them.
This is Friendship Seven. Am I in contact with anyone? Over.
Friendship Seven, Friendship Seven. This is Guaymas Com Tech, Guaymas Com Tech, transmitting on HF-UHF. Do you read? Over.
Hello, Guaymas Com Tech, Guaymas Com Tech. This is Friendship Seven. Receive your HF loud and clear. How me? Over.
Friendship Seven, Friendship Seven. This is Guaymas Cap Com. You're little garbled right now, but understandable. What is, what is your status? Over.
This is Friendship Seven on HF. My status is excellent. Everything is going according to plan. Control fuel is 90-100, oxygen is 72-101, amps 22. Over.
Friendship Seven, Guaymas Cap Com. Everything looks fine from here.
Roger. This is Friendship Seven. Understand everything looks okay.
This is Friendship Seven. I still have some of these very small particles coming around the capsule. Over.
Roger, Friendship Seven.
Friendship Seven, Guaymas Cap Com. Could you go to UHF now?
Roger. This is Friendship Seven, going to UHF.
Hello, Guaymas, Friendship Seven on UHF. Do you receive? Over.
Roger, Friendship Seven, loud and clear. Over.
Hello, Roger, this is Friendship Seven. Loud and clear with you also. Are we still go from Control Center? Over.
Roger, we're still go.
Friendship Seven, Guaymas. Do you want your contingency times now? Over.
[Press ROGER when you are ready to copy. You can optionally use the MISSION TOOLS -> Forms -> MA-6 Retrosequence times form]
This is Friendship Seven. Ready to copy.
Area 2 Alpha 01 36 38. Area Golf 03 00 41.
[COPY]
Area Hotel is 04 32 40.
[COPY]
Friendship Seven, Guaymas Cap Com. We have a scope retract indication on ground. Believe it's ground failure. Over.
That is affirmative. The scope is extended. The scope is extended. Over.
This is Friendship Seven. Yaw is drifting out of orbit attitude and will bring it back in. Over.
Roger.
[Switch to FBW and manually stop the yaw attitude rate.]
[Bring Yaw back to 0 degrees and stop rates.]
This is Friendship Seven. Back on ASCS.
Friendship Seven, Guaymas. You were on ASCS when it started drifting out. Over.
That is affirmative.
[Still drifting, switch to FBW and null the yaw rate]
[Bring the craft back to orbit attitude with Yaw 0 degrees]
This is Friendship Seven. Now on fly-by-wire to hold orbit attitude.
This is Friendship Seven. I have the land in sight out the window. Controlling manually, on fly-by-wire.
Friendship Seven. Is the ASCS OK now? Over.
I'll switch back on to it now and see.
[Switch to ASCS]
This is Friendship Seven. Negative.

This is Friendship Seven. It drifts out about 20 to the right and then gets a large pulse to kick it back over to the left. It goes in about, the rate runs over to about 3 degrees per second, to the left.
[Switch back to FBW and bring the craft back to a stable orbit attitude, and maintain orbit attitude.]
Cape Com Tech. Do you read? Over.
Roger, Cape Com Tech. Friendship Seven. Over.
Friendship Seven, Canaveral Com Tech. Read you loud and clear. Standby for Cap Com. Over.
Roger.
